                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1278a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-09T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 9, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>85. “Personal from the President to Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek. We are rapidly
                    increasing our ferry service to China via Africa and India. I can now give you
                    definite assurances that even though there should be a further setback in
                    Rangoon, which now seems improbable, the supply route to China via India can be
                    maintained by air.</p>
                <p>The whole plan seems altogether practical and I am sure we can make it a reality
                    in the near future. Roosevelt.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
